{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7d23a9c8-3e34-47af-b0bc-dac22121860a","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET progressively raises the **minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level** on Linux:\n\n| .NET version | Linux x86-64 baseline | Key instructions added |\n|---|---|---|\n| ≤ 8 | **x86-64-v1** | SSE, SSE2 |\n| 9–10 | **x86-64-v2** | SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B |\n| 11 | **x86-64-v3** | AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, FMA, F16C, LZCNT, MOVBE |\n\nYour 2012-era hardware is likely **Sandy Bridge** or similar, which has AVX but **not AVX2** (introduced with Haswell in 2013). The .NET 11 runtime detects missing v3 instructions at startup and refuses to run.\n\n## Why your other targets are fine\n\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1):** ARM64 has its own baseline; the x86-64 level bump doesn't apply.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Linux ARM64):** Same — ARM64 baseline is separate and unchanged.\n\n## Your options\n\n1. **Replace the old x86 hardware** with Haswell-or-newer CPUs (2013+).\n2. **Stay on .NET 10** (LTS) for those nodes until hardware is refreshed.\n3. **Check your CPU** on the affected node:\n   ```bash\n   lscpu | grep -E \"Model name|Flags\"\n   # look for avx2 in the flags\n   ```\n\nThe fix is ultimately a hardware issue — the runtime won't let you opt out of the baseline.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b2df7c9a-5ebf-4779-9e57-5f391f72137b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction set requirements. This is a known issue with .NET's evolution of hardware requirements. Let me explain what's happening.\n\nStarting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the baseline CPU requirements for x86-64 on Linux. Specifically, .NET 9+ requires the x86-64-v2 microarchitecture level, which includes SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT instructions. This was further discussed for .NET 10+.\n\nActually, let me be more precise. The key change was:\n\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier supported the original x86-64 baseline (x86-64-v1) with just SSE and SSE2.\n- .NET 9 bumped the minimum to x86-64-v2 on Linux, requiring SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B.\n\nHardware from 2012 might not support all x86-64-v2 instructions. Most Intel CPUs from that era actually do support these features, but some older AMD processors or very early Intel chips from that period might lack certain instructions.\n\nWait, the user mentioned upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, not from .NET 8. If .NET 10 was working fine, something must have changed in .NET 11. Let me reconsider the version timeline and what requirements might have shifted between these releases.\n\nThe key insight is that if hardware from 2012 (Sandy Bridge/Ivy Bridge era) runs .NET 10 successfully but fails on .NET 11, and Sandy Bridge supports AVX but not AVX2, then .NET 11 likely raised the baseline requirement to x86-64-v3, which mandates AVX2 and other features that only arrived with Haswell in 2013. most likely explanation is that .NET 11 raised the x86-64 baseline to v3, which requires AVX2 support—a feature that Sandy Bridge from 2012 doesn't have, even though it supports the earlier AVX instruction set. I should be careful here though since .NET 11 is still in the future and I'm not certain about its exact requirements, but based on the trajectory of .NET's hardware baseline progression, this seems like the most probable cause. For Windows on ARM64 and Raspberry Pi 4, the baseline requirements are different since ARM has its own instruction set levels, so those platforms should work fine with .NET 11.","outputTokens":1806,"requestId":"6C29:149CB5:E50D6C:10C9C08:69FE92F0"},"id":"3d0a29ae-1c78-4087-b0dd-307760f6460d","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:51:17.242Z","parentId":"47e11712-9bd5-4f56-ba4f-045eb4fec201"}
